by Vadterland » Mon Mar 15, 2021 5:04 pm

Outside of the existence of Nacrad itself, their world's geopolitical situation is divergent from our own but similar in a number of ways. The Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact still exist and Europe remains divided into East and West, Afghanistan is divided between different ideologically motivated warlord factions, Iran still had its Islamic revolution, Iraq still got George Bush'd, and Syria is still on fire. Ironically South America might be the place that has seen the most change out of all of the continents, with a massive unholy blob of a pro-American dictatorship being propped up by the US made up of Colombia, Venezuela, Peru, Ecuador, the Guianas and the Amazon, and Argentina and Chile remaining as full-on fascist dictatorships rather than just military juntas.

Map is a bit hard to read, though. Way too many shades of the same color makes it hard to tell which countries are which in the whole scheme of the map even if they are politically/ideologically aligned.

The current state of world affairs in Tellus has led to the formation of an "Atlantic Concordat" which in the context of the setting appears to be an alternative to NATO, featuring Atlantia, Albion, and her commonwealth dominions in the ANGLOSPHERE. Notably, it's much more Anglo-centric, likely as a result of the Germanians emerging as a significant power bloc in Eastern Europe, and thus it's likely to act much more as a defense treaty between nations bound together by their common heritages than by the big bad reds- especially since said reds don't exist in the form they did otl.

Note that some of this is reading between the lines based on the map of spheres of influence and of the flavor text for other nations in the world affairs factbook.

The Waisnor Constitution states that the country must be divided into equally-populated constituencies (currently a little less than 29,000 per constituency). This feels like it would make it quite difficult to actually provide the divide, given that a single city would end up being broken up into a number of constituencies (and which means that rural constituencies would end up being geographically massive in comparison and also have significantly less weight in the unicameral parliament, given how many more votes a single city of, say, 290,000 would have). It also doesn't seem to state whether or not the President, as Head of State, or Prime Minister, as Head of Government, dissolve the Government and Congress and call for early elections.
